# Frontend (Next.js + React Flow) conventions

- API calls go through the generated client (openapi-typescript / orval output
  from `api/openapi.yaml`), not hand-written `fetch` calls with inline types.
  If an endpoint you need isn't in the generated client, the contract is
  missing it — fix `api/openapi.yaml`, don't work around it locally.
- Default the client's base URL to the Prism mock server during local dev
  until the real backend endpoint is confirmed working; swap via env var, not
  by hardcoding a different URL in code.
- The node palette and node type config forms should be driven by the
  `GET /node-types` response, not a hardcoded list — adding a node type on the
  backend shouldn't require a matching hardcoded frontend change beyond the
  custom node's rendering component.
- React Flow (xyflow) custom node components live alongside their config form;
  keep node-type-specific logic isolated per node type rather than growing a
  single switch statement across the canvas code.
- Named exports, not default exports, for shared components.
- Server state (graph data, run status) via the generated client + your
  existing data-fetching pattern once one is chosen — don't introduce a second
  state-management library without discussing it first.
